    "url": "http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/2017/03/31/judge-rules-dog-bit-mailman-must-euthanized/99864606/",
    "title": "Judge rules dog that bit mailman must be euthanized",
    "author": "Matt Fagan",
    "publication_date": "2017-03-31T04:00:00.000Z",
    "source_id": 15,
    "text": "<div><div class=\"asset-double-wide double-wide p402_premium\"><div id=\"module-position-P2B_HQQgpLA\" class=\"story-asset video-asset\"><div class=\"ui-video-wrapper \"><div class=\"ui-pluto-video js-ui-video-init story-video inline-story-video priority smallarticleattophtml5 \"><div class=\"js-ptb pluto-title-bar\"><div class=\"js-ptb-close pluto-title-bar-vcenter pluto-title-bar-close\"><div>CLOSE<img class=\"pluto-title-bar-close-icon\" src=\"https://www.gannett-cdn.com/uxstatic/northjersey/uscp-web-static-2377.0/images/sprites/icon_close.png\"></div></div></div><div class=\"ui-pluto-still\"><img class=\"ui-pluto-still-img\" src=\"https://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/5460fdc7234ac0625ddcb2a29519058f84571973/c=878-1799-2778-2872&amp;r=1280x720&amp;r=540/local/-/media/2017/03/31/Bergen/NorthJersey/636265776952869207-GABBANA-15530013.JPG\" width=\"540px\"></div></div><div class=\"ui-video-controls story-video inline-story-video priority\"><p class=\"video-desc\"> Gabbana, a 2-year-old American Bully dog is scheduled to be euthanized after he bit off the tip of the mailman&apos;s finger last fall. His owner Jose Galvin, a Paterson police officer who lives in Vernon, is trying to save the dog&apos;s life and is appealing <span class=\"credit\">Matt Fagan/Edited by Jai Agnish</span></p></div></div></div><p>Gabbana, a 2-year-old American Bully&#xA0;will be euthanized for biting&#xA0;a&#xA0;mailman&#xA0;unless his owner can turn things around.</p><p>On March 13 a&#xA0;Wantage&#xA0;municipal judge&#xA0;classified&#xA0;the dog&#xA0;as&#xA0;vicious and&#xA0;ruled that he was to be euthanized. Gabbana&apos;s owner, a Paterson police officer who lives in Vernon with his wife, said he&#xA0;will fight&#xA0;to save his dog and will appeal&#xA0;the judge&apos;s&#xA0;decision.</p><p>The dog, which according to&#xA0;AmericanBullyDaily.com&#xA0;is&#xA0;a newer breed and an extension of the American Pit Bull Terrior with an infusion of English Bulldog, bit off the&#xA0;tip&#xA0;of a&#xA0;postal carrier&apos;s&#xA0;finger last September as he delivered packages to Jose and&#xA0;Raquel Galvin&apos;s home.</p><p>Galvin, a 16-year police officer, said he has seen his share of vicious dogs, and Gabbana is not one.</p><p>The postal carrier&#xA0;had been instructed verbally and in writing&#xA0;not to go on the property and to leave packages at the mailbox, which falls outside the home&apos;s&#xA0;invisible dog fence, said the attorney representing the&#xA0;Galvins.</p><p>Galvin said he fitted Gabbana with an invisible fence collar to keep him from running off or after deer.</p><div id=\"module-position-P2B_HQQxMuc\" class=\"story-asset image-asset\"><aside class=\"wide single-photo\"><img src=\"https://www.gannett-cdn.com/-mm-/1a43c73b321ea4e2e525f5b05d5912b8aa313471/c=0-25-3024-2299&amp;r=x408&amp;c=540x405/local/-/media/2017/03/31/Bergen/NorthJersey/636265777899651414-JOSE-15530015.JPG\" alt=\"Jose Galvin is a police office in the City of Paterson,\" width=\"540\"><meta><meta><meta><p>Jose Galvin is a police office in the City of Paterson,<meta>&#xA0;<span class=\"credit\">(Photo: Matt Fagan/NorthJersey.com, NJMG)</span></p></aside></div><p>On Sept. 16, 2016, the carrier walked on to&#xA0;the property in an attempt&#xA0;to deliver two packages, said&#xA0;Galvin. It was a trash pickup day, Galvin said, explaining the postal carrier has since&#xA0;told him he was concerned the packages would be mistaken for trash and end up in the garbage truck as the reason he walked toward the house.</p><p>The postal carrier was walking&#xA0;down the driveway&#xA0;toward the home when&#xA0;Gabbana&#xA0;ran out of the garage and toward him, Galvin said. Somehow the dog bit the tip of the carrier&apos;s finger, Galvin said. The dog, his owner said, was most likely going for the packages and grabbed the finger instead.</p><p>U.S.&#xA0;Postal Service&#xA0;Spokesman&#xA0;George&#xA0;&#xA0;Flood said&#xA0;the mail carrier involved&#xA0;was not available to be reached for comment.</p><p>&quot;The UPS and Fed Ex drivers&#xA0;also don&apos;t come all the way up the driveway,&quot;&#xA0;Galvin&#xA0;said. &quot;They&#xA0;leave&#xA0;the package and they carry dog treats.&quot;</p><p>Once when&#xA0;Gabanna&#xA0;wasn&apos;t wearing his shock collar, he&#xA0;ran and sat in the Federal Express truck, he said, not hurting anyone.</p><p>Galvin&apos;s attorney John McDermott,&#xA0; said&#xA0;he was able to reach an agreement with&#xA0;Wantage&#xA0;Prosecutor&#xA0;William Haggerty&#xA0;to change the classification from vicious to dangerous, which would save&#xA0;Gabanna&apos;s&#xA0;life. He said the postal carrier also expressed that he does not want the dog euthanized. The only thing standing in the way of the changed classification, McDermott said, is&#xA0;Vernon Township&apos;s&#xA0;animal&#xA0;control&#xA0;officer,&#xA0;Thomas&#xA0;Maellaro.</p><p>The dog was initially to be quarantined for 10 days but&#xA0;Maellaro, according to McDermott and Galvin, would not release Gabbana to the family.&#xA0;After three months in the Vernon animal shelter,&#xA0;Galvin&#xA0;said the animal control officer released&#xA0;the dog&#xA0;under the supervision of the&#xA0;Franklin&#xA0;Pet Spa. Gabbana is not allowed contact with any other dogs or people other than the&#xA0;Galvins&#xA0;and staff at the spa.</p><p>Marianne&#xA0;Sykes, a certified dog trainer and general manager at the spa,&#xA0;said she&#xA0;evaluated Gabbana and&#xA0;said she did not find him&#xA0;to be vicious.</p><p>&quot;I pulled his ears,&#xA0;his tail...stuck my hand in his mouth,&quot;&#xA0;and nothing happened,&#xA0;Sykes said. The trainer said she was able to get the dog to submit by rolling on his back, adding&#xA0;Gabbana could be home with his family.</p><p>McDermott said&#xA0;the next step is for Gabbana&apos;s case to be appealed to the Sussex County Superior Court. He is waiting for the transcripts from the&#xA0;Wantage&#xA0;court before he can file the paper work.&#xA0;McDermott and Galvin asked for the case to be heard in Wantage rather than Vernon.</p><p>The attorney said&#xA0;the chances of&#xA0;winning on appeal are good.&#xA0;McDermott said&#xA0;Vernon police and the&#xA0;animal control officers&#xA0;entered&#xA0;Galvin&apos;s property to get the dog without warrant circumventing their right to due process.&#xA0;He also&#xA0;said the court didn&apos;t allow the&#xA0;Galvins&#xA0;to enter Sykes&apos;&#xA0;evaluation into the record.</p><p>Galvin said he hopes the&#xA0;case&#xA0;will&#xA0;be settled before it gets to court. He is willing to declare Gabbana a dangerous dog, which would&#xA0;require a dangerous dog/no trespassing&#xA0;sign,&#xA0;an invisible fence,&#xA0;a fenced in kennel&#xA0;to be installed and&#xA0;tattoo warning people that his dog is consider dangerous.</p><p>&quot;We just want him home,&quot;&#xA0;Galvin&#xA0;said. He said his legal bills, so far, are at&#xA0;$10,000.</p><p>Maellaro&#xA0;did not return calls or emails seeking information.</p><p>When reached,&#xA0;Haggert&#xA0;said he had no comment.</p><p class=\"article-print-url\">Read or Share this story: https://njersy.co/2nJt2Hl</p></div><aside class=\"story-right-rail\"><section id=\"module-position-P2B_HQKtoCs\" class=\"storyrightrail-bucket poster-ad-asset-module story-poster-ad-asset-module\"></section><section id=\"module-position-P2B_HQLNXvw\" class=\"storyrightrail-bucket poster-ad-asset2-module story-poster-ad-asset2-module\"></section></aside></div>",
